+# Interpretation of stochastic alignment LR sweep
+
+The learning-rate sweep is supportive of the main theory.
+
+## Main positive evidence
+
+After tuning learning rates per optimizer and coordinate case:
+
+- aligned and band-limited coordinates keep adaptive methods in the `q_eff≈1/2` class;
+- flat and Haar coordinates keep adaptive methods in the `q_eff≈0` class;
+- spectral oracle keeps `q_eff=1/2` in every coordinate system;
+- coordinate oracle collapses to scalar-like behavior in flat/Haar coordinates.
+
+This separates finite-time constant improvements from spectral exponent improvements.
+
+## Key interpretation
+
+Flat/Haar Adam and RMSProp can still beat SGD in finite-time risk, but their measured `q_eff` is near zero.  Therefore their improvement is not coming from spectral flattening.  It is likely due to scalar normalization, transient adaptivity, or momentum-like constant effects.
+
+In flat/Haar coordinates, the spectral oracle strongly outperforms coordinate oracle, showing that the population spectrum is still exploitable, but it is not visible to coordinatewise second moments.
+
+## Next recommended run
+
+Run the controlled interpolation experiment:
+
+```bash
+python experiments/theta_profile_training_grid.py \
+  --dimension 2048 \
+  --theta-values 0,0.25,0.5,0.75,1 \
+  --lr-values 0.001,0.003,0.005,0.01,0.03 \
+  --checkpoints 250,500,1000,2000,4000,8000 \
+  --trials 5 \
+  --batch-size 16 \
+  --outdir experiments/results/theta_profile_training_grid
+```
+
+Expected result: after LR tuning, larger `theta` should monotonically improve the learned-mode/risk behavior, with predicted `q_eff=theta/2`.
