+# 17. Tuned scalar gains do not erase visible-spectrum exponent separation
+
+The learning-rate grid experiments show an important phenomenon: in flat or Haar coordinates, Adam/RMSProp can beat SGD in finite time even when the measured spectral diagnostic satisfies
+
+\[
+    q_{\rm eff}\approx 0.
+\]
+
+This is not a contradiction.  Scalar normalization, momentum, and learning-rate tuning can improve constants, but they cannot change the power-law spectral exponent unless the preconditioner changes the covariance spectrum by a polynomial amount.  This note formalizes that separation.
+
+## 1. General visible-spectrum family
+
+Let the effective eigenvalues after preconditioning obey
+
+\[
+    \widetilde\mu_i
+    \asymp
+    \lambda_i^{1-q},
+    \qquad
+    0\le q\le 1/2,
+\]
+
+before damping, where
+
+\[
+    \lambda_i\asymp i^{-a},
+    \qquad a>1.
+\]
+
+Equivalently,
+
+\[
+    \widetilde\mu_i\asymp i^{-\alpha(q)},
+    \qquad
+    \alpha(q)=a(1-q).
+\]
+
+The aligned Adam/RMSProp case has \(q=1/2\).  Scalar/flat/Haar coordinatewise adaptivity has \(q=0\).  The visible-profile theorem gives the intermediate family \(q=\theta/2\).
+
+Let the source condition be
+
+\[
+    s_i\asymp i^{-b},
+    \qquad
+    1<b<\alpha(q)+1.
+\]
+
+In the clean source range, the filter law is
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    R(M,n)-\sigma^2
+    \asymp
+    M^{1-b}
+    +n^{-(b-1)/\alpha(q)}
+    +\frac{n^{1/\alpha(q)}}{N_{\rm eff}},
+}
+\]
+
+when \(K(n)<M\), up to constants and logarithms.  In the hard-source phase where variance is lower order, the leading approximation/bias tradeoff is
+
+\[
+    M^{1-b}+n^{-(b-1)/\alpha(q)}.
+\]
+
+## 2. Learning-rate tuning changes constants, not exponents
+
+Let a tuned scalar gain replace \(n\\) by \(c n\), where \(0<c<\infty\) is allowed to depend on optimizer hyperparameters but not polynomially on \(n\).  Then
+
+\[
+    (c n)^{-(b-1)/\alpha(q)}
+    =
+    c^{-(b-1)/\alpha(q)} n^{-(b-1)/\alpha(q)}.
+\]
+
+The constant changes, but the exponent does not.
+
+More generally, if the preconditioner is scalar-comparable,
+
+\[
+    p_- I\preceq P\preceq p_+I,
+    \qquad p_+/p_-\le\kappa,
+\]
+
+then the transformed spectrum is sandwiched as
+
+\[
+    p_-\lambda_i\le \widetilde\mu_i\le p_+\lambda_i.
+\]
+
+Thus the learned-mode count satisfies
+
+\[
+    K(c_- n)\le K_P(n)
+    \le K(c_+ n),
+\]
+
+and for \(\lambda_i\asymp i^{-a}\),
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    K_P(n)\asymp n^{1/a}.
+}
+\]
+
+No scalar tuning can turn \(n^{1/a}\) into \(n^{2/a}\).
+
+## 3. Compute-optimal exponent separation
+
+Under the one-pass compute model
+
+\[
+    C\asymp MN,
+\]
+
+and ignoring logarithms and lower-order variance in the hard-source phase, optimize
+
+\[
+    M^{1-b}+N^{-(b-1)/\alpha(q)}
+    \qquad\text{subject to }MN=C.
+\]
+
+Balancing terms gives
+
+\[
+    M_\star(q)\asymp C^{1/[\alpha(q)+1]},
+    \qquad
+    N_\star(q)\asymp C^{\alpha(q)/[\alpha(q)+1]}.
+\]
+
+The compute-risk exponent is
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    R(C)-\sigma^2
+    \asymp
+    C^{-\beta(q)},
+    \qquad
+    \beta(q)=\frac{b-1}{a(1-q)+1}.
+}
+\]
+
+Since \(a>0\), \(\beta(q)\) is strictly increasing in \(q\).  Therefore any genuinely visible spectral preconditioner with \(q>0\) has a strictly better asymptotic compute exponent than a scalar/flat preconditioner.
+
+In particular,
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    \beta(1/2)-\beta(0)
+    =
+    (b-1)\left(
+        \frac{1}{a/2+1}
+        -
+        \frac{1}{a+1}
+    \right)>0.
+}
+\]
+
+This is the formal exponent separation between aligned/band-limited Adam/RMSProp and flat/Haar coordinatewise adaptivity.
+
+## 4. AdamW ceiling
+
+For AdamW, the visible-spectrum horizon is replaced by
+
+\[
+    n_{\rm eff}=\min\{n,\delta^{-1}\},
+\]
+
+where \(\delta\) is the effective decoupled weight-decay threshold.  Thus the exponent separation persists only while
+
+\[
+    n\lesssim \delta^{-1}.
+\]
+
+To preserve the compute-optimal exponent at scale \(C\), weight decay must satisfy
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    \delta\lesssim N_\star(q)^{-1}
+    \asymp
+    C^{-\alpha(q)/[\alpha(q)+1]}.
+}
+\]
+
+Fixed positive weight decay creates a ceiling and eventually saturates the learned-mode count.
+
+## 5. Interpretation of the learning-rate grid experiment
+
+The learning-rate sweep can be interpreted as follows.
+
+* In aligned and band-limited coordinates, the best RMSProp/Adam/AdamW runs have \(q_{\rm eff}\approx 1/2\).  They are in the better exponent class.
+* In flat and Haar coordinates, the best RMSProp/Adam/AdamW runs have \(q_{\rm eff}\approx0\).  They may still improve constants and finite-time risk, but they are in the scalar exponent class.
+* A spectral oracle in flat/Haar coordinates recovers \(q=1/2\), showing that the missing ingredient is not the covariance spectrum itself but the visibility of that spectrum to coordinatewise second moments.
+
+Thus the high-impact claim should not be phrased as "Adam always improves scaling exponents."  The correct claim is:
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    \text{Adam/RMSProp improve scaling exponents exactly when their second moments expose a nontrivial spectral profile.}
+}
+\]
+
+## 6. Next empirical diagnostic
+
+The next experiment should vary \(q\) continuously through a controlled visible profile
+
+\[
+    P_{\theta,i}=(\lambda_i^\theta+\rho)^{-1/2},
+    \qquad q=\theta/2,
+\]
+
+and run stochastic training with learning-rate tuning.  The predicted compute/data exponent should improve monotonically with \(\theta\).  This is implemented in
+
+```text
+experiments/theta_profile_training_grid.py
+```
+
+and is the cleanest stochastic test of the continuum theorem before moving to more realistic random-feature maps.
